\section*{Problem}

A car travels at a constant speed of 14.0 m/s around a level circular bend of radius 45 m. What is the minimum coefficient of static friction between the tyres and the road in order for the car to go round the bend without skidding? [University of Manchester 2008]

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{3.1}

The parametric equations for a circular path are given by:
\begin{align}
    x &= a \cos t \quad \text{(1)} \\
    y &= a \sin t \quad \text{(2)} \\
    z &= t \quad \text{(3)}
\end{align}

Squaring equations (1) and (2) and adding them, we get:
\begin{align*}
    x^2 + y^2 &= a^2 (\cos^2 t + \sin^2 t) = a^2
\end{align*}
which is the equation of a circle. Since \( z = t \), the circular path drifts along the \( z \)-axis so that the path is a helix.

\subsection*{3.2}

The acceleration \( a \) is given by:
\[
a = \frac{dv}{dt} = k^2 r t^2
\]

The velocity \( v \) is obtained by integrating:
\[
v = \int dv = k^2 r \int t^2 \, dt = k^2 r \frac{t^3}{3}
\]

The power \( P \) is given by:
\[
P = Fv = mav = mk^2 r t^2 \cdot k^2 r \frac{t^3}{3} = \frac{mk^4 r^2 t^5}{3}
\]

